<div id="review_3700196068" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3700196068" />
    <a title="Daniel Montague" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27910812-daniel-montague"><img alt="Daniel Montague" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1390330145p2/27910812.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3700196068?book_show_action=true">Dec 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Daniel Montague" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Daniel Montague" href="/user/show/27910812-daniel-montague">Daniel Montague</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27910812-daniel-montague?shelf=quick-read">quick-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27910812-daniel-montague?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27910812-daniel-montague?shelf=biography">biography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27910812-daniel-montague?shelf=takedowns">takedowns</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3700196068" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4618502213213585741">Trash talk, verbal jousting, shit talking; whatever you call it Christopher Hitchens is an expert at it. Like any great polemic, this one cuts deep because it is so honest. The most painful thing about trash talk is its accuracy. Besides, a racial epithet or an euphemism for a lady part, there is nothing that will cause a fracas quicker than an accurate statement. What makes Hitchens so wonderful, is that he peels away the facade of Mother Teresa and reveals not only a person with many faults bu</span>
  <span id="freeText4618502213213585741" style="display:none">Trash talk, verbal jousting, shit talking; whatever you call it Christopher Hitchens is an expert at it. Like any great polemic, this one cuts deep because it is so honest. The most painful thing about trash talk is its accuracy. Besides, a racial epithet or an euphemism for a lady part, there is nothing that will cause a fracas quicker than an accurate statement. What makes Hitchens so wonderful, is that he peels away the facade of Mother Teresa and reveals not only a person with many faults but a monster who exploits her notions of piety to further her own goals while depriving those you need it most. <br /><br />The prevailing view of Mother Teresa is that of a saint who devoted her existence to serving the poorest of the poor. She is often noted as the very symbol of piety and rightfulness. Through innumerable examples, Mr. Hitchens is able to build the case that Mother Teresa is far from saintly. His case is strongest in showing the strange bedfellows who cozy up to her and who she hobnobs with. Whether it is the disgraced dictator Baby Doc Duvalier in Haiti or a rich financier who destroyed many peoples livelihoods and pensions; she has a slew of less than desirable friendships. She even had close ties to a Communist regime in her native Albania which billed itself as "the first atheist state of the world." In addition, she became a poster child for conservative Christian politicians such as Ronald Reagan, Margaret Thatcher and Ralph Reed. <br /><br />While, having photo ops with less than savory characters is bad enough the payoff is where the horrific side of Teresa comes through. Meeting with so many wealthy and powerful dignitaries should provide both monetary and influential benefits but to look at the conditions of Teresa's inhabitants would tell a different story. Her and her missionaries were literally making money hand over fist and the people she was supposed to empower were still living in squalor. Instead of investing in a sound infrastructure or a clinic that could have served innumerable people in the areas she operated in; the money went into an unaccounted slush fund. If not providing basic sanitation was bad enough she couched the bad conditions in biblical terms, and held up misery and suffering as positives. She used the idea of sacrifice to continue the rancid conditions of her victims even though she had the means to change their lives. If that was not bad enough, she used her saintly presence to further hurt people. She was stridently against any form of birth control and had the audacity to make any discussion on contraceptives into a political one.<br /><br />Though I have largely lived a life not involving overly pious people, Mr. Hitchens in his takedown of Mother Teresa has shown the danger that such people pose. He was able to show even in the example of the esteemed holy nun Teresa there still lurks a fanaticism that can have costly consequences. He was able to write an informative and educational work on a disgraceful person. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4618502213213585741" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


